---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';
import ProgressiveOverloadCalculator from '../../components/calculators/ProgressiveOverloadCalculator.astro';
---

<ToolLayout
  title="Progressive Overload Calculator"
  description="Calculate optimal weight progression and training volume increases for sustained progress. Specifically designed for men over 40."
>
  <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none mb-8">
    <h2>Smart Progression After 40</h2>
    <p>
      Progressive overload remains essential for building strength and muscle after 40, but it needs to be approached
      differently. This calculator helps you plan sustainable progress while accounting for recovery capacity and joint health.
    </p>
    
    <div class="my-6">
      <h3>Key Progression Factors</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Recovery Capacity:</strong> Affects how quickly you can increase load</li>
        <li><strong>Joint Health:</strong> Influences progression strategy</li>
        <li><strong>Training History:</strong> Determines realistic progression rates</li>
        <li><strong>Exercise Type:</strong> Different progressions for different movements</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <ProgressiveOverloadCalculator />

  <div class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none mt-8">
    <div class="my-6 p-4 bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 rounded-lg">
      <h3 class="mt-0">Understanding Your Results</h3>
      
      <h4>Weekly Progression Guidelines</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Weight Increases:</strong> Smaller, more frequent jumps for sustainability</li>
        <li><strong>Volume Changes:</strong> Gradual increases in sets and reps</li>
        <li><strong>Deload Timing:</strong> Strategic recovery periods</li>
        <li><strong>Exercise Rotation:</strong> When to modify exercise selection</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Important Considerations</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Progress should feel challenging but manageable</li>
        <li>Form must be maintained with increased loads</li>
        <li>Recovery between sessions is crucial</li>
        <li>Adjust progression based on energy levels</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Implementing Progressive Overload</h2>

    <h3>Methods of Progression</h3>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Primary Methods</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Increase weight</li>
          <li>Add repetitions</li>
          <li>Add sets</li>
          <li>Decrease rest periods</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Advanced Techniques</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Tempo manipulation</li>
          <li>Range of motion increases</li>
          <li>Movement complexity</li>
          <li>Density improvements</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3>Exercise-Specific Guidelines</h3>
    <div class="bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-800 p-4 rounded-lg">
      <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Compound Lifts</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Smaller weight jumps (2.5-5 lbs)</li>
        <li>Focus on quality reps</li>
        <li>Longer rest periods allowed</li>
        <li>Regular deload weeks</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 dark:bg-blue-900 p-4 rounded-lg mt-6">
      <h3 class="text-blue-900 dark:text-blue-100 mt-0">Progress Monitoring Tips</h3>
      <ul class="text-blue-800 dark:text-blue-200">
        <li>Keep detailed training logs</li>
        <li>Track both weight and reps</li>
        <li>Note exercise quality</li>
        <li>Monitor recovery between sessions</li>
        <li>Record energy levels</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6">
      <h3>When to Adjust Your Progression</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Form deteriorates with increased load</li>
        <li>Recovery becomes insufficient</li>
        <li>Joint discomfort develops</li>
        <li>Plateau persists beyond 2-3 weeks</li>
        <li>Energy levels consistently decrease</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</ToolLayout>
